{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487513"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.22,0.04,0.23,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"27158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/363"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14085"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"9005"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"27158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/27158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents with a two-month history of increasing deafness in his right ear and a three-week history of painless swelling in the right side of his neck. He has never had these symptoms before. He has not noticed any dizziness or ringing in his ear. He has not lost any weight but has noticed some mild fatigue recently. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks about four cans of beer a day, with no alcohol-free days. He is of Malaysian origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vitals are all normal and he has a normal body habitus. There is a painless enlargement of the jugulodigastric nodes on the right side of the neck. Otoscopy demonstrates a middle ear effusion on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound-guided biopsy of lymph nodes","Visualisation of the nasopharynx","Audiogram","MRI head and neck","CT head and neck"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s deafness, swelling of his jugulodigastric lymph nodes, and fatigue, he may have a nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Whilst uncommon, these tumours are most frequently seen in individuals of Southeast Asian origin. They commonly present with increasing deafness, secondary to obstruction of the eustachian tube or nasal symptoms (obstruction, discharge). \u003Cstrong\u003EVisualisation of the nasopharynx\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step to investigate this possible differential further.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough imaging such as \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003ECT of the head and neck\u003C/strong\u003E may be required to assess bone extension and intracranial invasion of the tumour, these would not be conducted before examining the nasopharynx. Of these, MRI is the preferred modality due to its ability to detect nodal metastasis and soft tissue extension of the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eaudiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful further on down the track if hearing loss persists, to document the type and degree of hearing loss that this patient has; however, it is certainly not the next step in management. Far more urgent is working up the possibility of nasopharyngeal carcinoma in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound-guided biopsy of the lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this patient as he is presenting with symptoms that may pertain to a cause of an enlarged lymph node.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma can involve lymph nodes of the apex of the posterior triangle of the neck initially (jugulodigastric nodes).","In patients with symptoms suspicious of nasopharyngeal carcinoma, examination of the nasal cavity should be performed.","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma can present with otological symptoms such as deafness and tinnitus, secondary to Eustachian tube blockage."],"references":["Chen YP, Chan ATC, Le QT, Blanchard P, Sun Y, Ma J. Nasopharyngeal carcinoma. Lancet. 2019 Jul 6;394(10192):64-80. DOI: 10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30956-0. Epub 2019 Jun 6. PMID: 31178151."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14085"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/14085"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-08-27T20:11:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T17:06:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"363"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"27158"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data